intuition : after looking at problem what i realized this is a sliding window pattern with dynamix window size , so my approach was i will find the frequency map of charcaters and i am going to add characters till size of frequency map is equal to given k , if size of frequency map gets larger than k , i will delete elements from dictionary till , frequency map gets to right size , once the frequency map gets to right size , i will calculate the max length of substring and return it as answer 

approach: 
take 2 pointers high = 0 low =0 
# high for adding elements in the frequency map and low for removing elements 
initalize max_length = -1 (if there is no substring with k dictinct characters)
create empty dictionary freq ={}
traverse the string using loop condition
for high in range(len(s)):
     first add elements inside frequency map as frequency map is initally empty
      freq[s[high]] = freq.get(s[high],0) + 1
     then check for condition if len(freq) > k:
            remove elements from frequency map , if frequency of an element becomes zero remove it      from frequency map , after removing element , move low pointer by +1 , 

then check required condition if len(freq) == k :
then calculate length of substring = right - left + 1
find max of max_length and length 

return max_length

# time complexity O(n+m)
# space complexity O(n)

code :
class Solution:
    def longestKSubstr(self, s, k):
        # code here
        low = 0
        high = 0
        max_length = -1
        freq = {}
        
        for high in range(len(s)):
            freq[s[high]] = freq.get(s[high] , 0) + 1
            
            while len(freq) > k:
                freq[s[low]] -= 1
                if freq[s[low]] == 0:
                    del freq[s[low]]
                low += 1
            
            if len(freq) == k:
                length = high - low + 1
                max_length = max(length , max_length)
        
        return max_length
                
                
         
